               <p>1451. <persName id="def1-1451-18390408" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1451-18390408" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1451-18390408" type="age" value="21"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1451-18390408" type="surname" value="BRAGG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1451-18390408" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM BRAGG</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18390408-1451-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1451-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1451-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp>for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1619" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1619" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1619" type="surname" value="DOWLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1619" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN DOWLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Edward Downey, a baker, at Upper Tooting. The prisoner lived with us about twelve months as journeyman—he was entrusted to receive money on his masters account for bread which he took out—he ought to account for the money he received the same day—he did not account for the receipt of any</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183904080235"></xptr>
               <p>money on the 28th of March from Mrs. Newbury, who is a customer of ours—we had suspicions the night he received this 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he was asked for it, and denied having it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was your husband unwell? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the prisoner did not manage the business—he did not make the bread—he ought to have paid the 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on Thursday—he was taken in custody on the Saturday—there was a balance of 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. then due to him, not a week's wages—he was not in the habit of deducting his wages from the money he received—I was not always present when he settled with my husband—he was going away a month before, and we increased his wages 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week, I think, to stay.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1620" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1620" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1620" type="surname" value="NEWBURT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1620" type="given" value="CHARLOTTE"></interp>CHARLOTTE NEWBURT</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Lower Tooting. I dealt with the prosecutor for bread which the prisoner brought—on the 28th of March I paid him 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on his master's account, between twelve and one o'clock in the day—he receipted the bill—it was 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., but there was a mistake in it of 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., which he took off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1621" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1621" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1621" type="surname" value="PEARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1621" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM PEARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I apprehended the prisoner at the prosecutor's house, on Saturday the 30th of March—I told told I took him for receiving Mrs. Newbury's bill—he said he had received it, and if his master would allow him a little time, he would contrive to make the money up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. DOWLEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know whether he had received say other money on his master's account the same day as the 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not to my knowledge—we had overlooked other things which he had committed before?</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18390408-1451-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1451-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1451-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi>. Aged 21. <hi rend="italic">—Recommended to mercy.</hi>
                  </rs>—
<rs id="t18390408-1451-punishment-276" type="punishmentDescription">
